    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1915-01-28T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1915-01-28T00:00:00-05:00" n="1480"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1480">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 855.48/176</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Belgium</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_WB1"
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Whitlock</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the</hi>
                    <gloss type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Secretary of State</hi>
                    </gloss>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 47]</seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Brussels</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1915-01-28">
                            <hi rend="italic">January 28, 1915</hi>.</date>
                        <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received February 15</hi>.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have the honor to transmit copies and
                    translation of a letter from the German military authorities informing me that
                    cattle and their food will hereafter be exempt from military requisition when
                    imported by the Comité National de Secours et d’Alimentation.</p>
                <p>I have [etc.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_WB1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Brand Whitlock</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
                <pb facs="1290" n="1032" xml:id="pg_1032"/>
                <frus:attachment>
                    <opener>
                        <seg rendition="#center">[Enclosure—Translation]</seg>
                    </opener>
                    <head>
                        <hi rend="italic">The Chief Administrator for the German Governor General in
                            Belgium</hi> (<persName type="from">
                            <hi rend="italic">Von Sandt</hi>
                        </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the American Minister</hi> (<persName
                            corresp="#p_WB1" type="to">
                            <hi rend="italic">Whitlock</hi>
                        </persName>)</head>
                    <opener>
                        <dateline rendition="#right">
                            <placeName>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Brussels</hi>
                            </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1915-01-13">
                                <hi rend="italic">January 13, 1915</hi>.</date>
                        </dateline>
                    </opener>
                    <p>I have the honor to inform your excellency that the Governor General in a
                        decision given on the 5th of this month has exempted from military
                        requisition not only foodstuffs imported by the Comité National de Secours
                        et d’Alimentation into Belgium from abroad for the civil population, but has
                        extended this measure to food necessary for beasts and cattle imported by
                        the committee.</p>
                    <p>Furthermore, as a consequence of the attached order<note n="1"
                            xml:id="d1480fn1">Not printed.</note> issued December 26 by the Governor
                        General, certain classes of animals are protected against military
                        requisition.</p>
                    <p>In this manner many of the wishes expressed by the National Committee’s
                        agricultural section are met.</p>
                    <p>I have [etc.]</p>
                    <closer>
                        <signed>
                            <persName>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">D. von Sandt</hi>
                            </persName>
                        </signed>
                    </closer>
                </frus:attachment>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
